{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3556114,"name":"CJ Hopkins","username":"CJHopkins","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/cjhopkins/{size}/254847_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-13T15:18:54.357Z","cooked":"<p>Good morning,</p>
<p>I have been speedrunning our code base over the last 24 hours, and came across something that I couldn’t wrap my head around…</p>
<p>This is the drive.java file for our robot:</p>
<p>package frc.robot;</p>
<p>import com.revrobotics.spark.SparkLowLevel.MotorType;<br>
import com.revrobotics.spark.SparkMax;<br>
import com.revrobotics.spark.config.SparkBaseConfig.IdleMode;<br>
import com.revrobotics.spark.config.SparkMaxConfig;</p>
<p>import edu.wpi.first.util.sendable.SendableRegistry;<br>
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj.XboxController;<br>
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj.drive.DifferentialDrive;<br>
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.CommandScheduler;<br>
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.SubsystemBase;<br>
import frc.robot.constants.drive_constants;</p>
<p>public class drive extends SubsystemBase{</p>
<pre><code>static SparkMax front_left = new SparkMax(drive_constants.front_left, MotorType.kBrushless);
static SparkMax front_right = new SparkMax(drive_constants.front_right, MotorType.kBrushless);
static SparkMax back_left = new SparkMax(drive_constants.back_left, MotorType.kBrushless);
static SparkMax back_right = new SparkMax(drive_constants.back_right, MotorType.kBrushless);
static DifferentialDrive robot_drive;
static XboxController controller = new XboxController(0);

public drive() {

    prepare_drive();
    robot_drive = new DifferentialDrive(front_left::set, front_right::set);
    differential_start();

}

public static void prepare_drive(){

    SparkMaxConfig back_left_config = new SparkMaxConfig();
    SparkMaxConfig front_left_config = new SparkMaxConfig();
    SparkMaxConfig back_right_config = new SparkMaxConfig();
    SparkMaxConfig front_right_config = new SparkMaxConfig();

    back_left_config.follow(drive_constants.front_left, false).idleMode(IdleMode.kBrake);
    back_right_config.follow(drive_constants.front_right, false).idleMode(IdleMode.kBrake);
    front_left_config.idleMode(IdleMode.kBrake).inverted(false);
    front_right_config.idleMode(IdleMode.kBrake).inverted(false);

    back_left.configure(back_left_config, null, null);
    back_right.configure(back_right_config, null, null);
    front_left.configure(front_left_config, null, null);
    front_right.configure(front_right_config, null, null);

}

public static void differential_start(){

    SendableRegistry.addChild(robot_drive, front_right);
    SendableRegistry.addChild(robot_drive, front_left);

}

public static void start_drive(){

    robot_drive.tankDrive(-controller.getRawAxis(1), controller.getRawAxis(5), true);

}

public static void brake(){

    front_left.set(0);
    front_right.set(0);
    CommandScheduler.getInstance().cancelAll();

}

public void autopilot(double speed){

    front_left.set(speed);
    front_right.set(speed);

}

public void autopilotback(){

    front_left.set(0.2);
    front_right.set(0.2);

}

public void autopilotleft(){

    front_left.set(0.3);
    front_right.set(-0.3);

}

public void autopilotright(){

    front_left.set(-0.3);
    front_right.set(0.3);

}

public void TurboBoost(){

    front_left.set(-10);
    front_right.set(-10);

}
</code></pre>
<p>}</p>
<p>It works as expected, without any major issues (the motors are jerky, which is not good, but I don’t know if that’s my fault or the hardware team’s).  The issue lies in the fact that we would rather use arcadeDrive than tankDrive.  When I switch it, changing nothing else in the file, the forward/backward drive is reversed, and turning the robot (i.e. input to the z-rotation axis) causes the motors to jam (i.e. front left and front back go in opposite directions).  This seems like it should not be possible, especially as the tankDrive worked with no issues.  curvatureDrive had the same issue.</p>
<p>I considered the canIDs being incorrect, but we double checked those and found no issues.</p>
<p>Is this a common problem?  I am upgrading VSCode to 2025.3.1 from 2025.1.1 now, but I don’t expect that to change much.  Any advice would be greatly appreciated (one day away from competition <img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/images/emoji/google/scream.png?v=12" title=":scream:" class="emoji" alt=":scream:" loading="lazy" width="20" height="20">)!</p>
<p>Thanks,</p>
<p>CJH</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":3,"updated_at":"2025-03-13T16:22:52.395Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":8,"reads":53,"readers_count":52,"score":50.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":495450,"topic_slug":"arcadedrive-method-not-working","display_username":"CJ Hopkins","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":74039,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/arcadedrive-method-not-working/495450/1","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3556276,"name":"abuddies","username":"abuddies","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/abuddies/{size}/254804_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-13T18:06:55.610Z","cooked":"<p>I’m not exactly sure what the issue is, but I have a couple of things you could try and a few general concepts.</p>
<p>Firstly, one of your sets of wheels should <em>most likely</em> be inverted. In the code, you have<br>
<code>front_left_config.idleMode(IdleMode.kBrake).inverted(false);     front_right_config.idleMode(IdleMode.kBrake).inverted(false);</code><br>
but one of those inverted()s should most likely be true. Which one it is depends on how your gears are oriented which connect to your wheels… So I would recommend manually rotating the wheels (either using REV Hardware Client or by writing some test code in Robot.java that just sets speeds to only one side of the wheels). A positive number should mean a movement forwards (for Arcade Drive).</p>
<p>If you want to test something, I would try making the right side of your wheels inverted based on how your right joystick is not currently inverted.</p>
<p>Also, instead of using <code>getRawAxis(1)</code>, I would recommend using <code>getLeftY()</code> which both do the same things, but getLeftY() will help you understand exactly which part of the joystick is doing the movement (in this case, the left joystick’s y-axis). From my experience with XBoxControllers, the y-axis is always negative going upwards (pain), so that negative sign you already have in the code is good.</p>
<p>Lastly, this is just me being concerned about the well being of your motors, the <code>set()</code> function of your motors accepts a percentage technically (a value between 0 to 1 where 1=100% full voltage), so in your <code>TurboBoost()</code> function, setting the speed to -10, or -1000%, will probably not be very good for your motors in the long term…</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":3,"updated_at":"2025-03-13T18:06:55.610Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":27,"readers_count":26,"score":10.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":495450,"topic_slug":"arcadedrive-method-not-working","display_username":"abuddies","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":61033,"hidden":false,"trust_level":0,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/arcadedrive-method-not-working/495450/2","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3556593,"name":"CJ Hopkins","username":"CJHopkins","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/cjhopkins/{size}/254847_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-13T22:55:27.916Z","cooked":"<p>I don’t think that the inverted motors are the issue…if they were, then I don’t see how it could function with tankDrive();.  I will definitely switch out the getRawAxis…left over from an older controller I think.</p>
<p>The turbo boost is more of a joke…it isn’t actually referenced anywhere else – thanks anyway though.</p>
<p>Anyway, I can’t get any testing time with the robot before competition, so I might end up sticking with tank until then.  If anything else comes to mind, I would greatly appreciate it.</p>
<p>Thanks again,</p>
